{{Quote|They said it was dangerous. I'll never understand, in a million years, how my daughter can be a danger. They're guardians of peace and justice. Well, how is letting me see her again a threat to peace and justice? Who is the monster? Is it me? Is it her? I don't think so.|Jonava Billane, in her appearance on the talk show ''Essence''|<ref name="motherslove">{{HoloNetNewsWeb|50|jediwatch/1344_1.html|Jedi Vs. The Force of a Mother's Love}}</ref>}}
After a destructive [[Groundquake/Legends|groundquake]] destroyed the [[Planet/Legends|planet]] [[Ord Thoden]]'s [[Capital/Legends|capital]] [[City/Legends|city]] of [[Domitree]] in [[23 BBY/Legends|23 BBY]], a crew of [[Jedi/Legends|Jedi]] rescue workers found an infant [[Force-sensitive/Legends|Force-sensitive]] girl named [[Aris-Del Wari|Ludi Billane]] alive in the wreckage and assuming she was an orphan, took her to [[Coruscant/Legends|Coruscant]] for [[Jedi training/Legends|training]]. When the girl's mother, [[Jonava Billane]], was discovered alive a [[Standard month/Legends|month]] later, a highly-publicized '''custody case''' began as Billane attempted to get her daughter back from the [[Jedi Order/Legends|Jedi Order]]. Backed by the Jedi watchdog group known as the [[People's Inquest]], Billane's efforts generated a large amount of media attention and public sympathy, although her formal petition for her daughter's return was rejected by the [[Jedi High Council/Legends|Jedi Council]], who said it was too dangerous to return the child to her parents after her mind had been opened to [[The Force/Legends|the Force]]. After a tearful appearance on the popular [[Eriadu/Legends|Eriadu]] talk show ''[[Essence]]'' attracted billions of viewers, Billane's case caused even more popular furor, including constant protests by the People's Inquest and even a brief, aborted storming of the [[Jedi Temple/Legends|Jedi Temple]] by local students. However, the Jedi Council stayed silent, and in [[22 BBY/Legends|22 BBY]] "Baby Ludi"&mdash;whom the Jedi had renamed Aris-Del Wari&mdash;was moved to a [[Kamparas Jedi Training Center|Jedi Training Center]] on [[Kamparas]]. Jonava Billane and People's Inquest leader [[Thrynka Padaunete]] were busy working on a [[Untitled Baby Ludi Project|holofeature]] on the "Baby Ludi" story at the time, and had no response.

==Prelude==
In [[23 BBY/Legends|23 BBY]], a [[Groundquake/Legends|groundquake]] devastated the [[City/Legends|city]] of [[Domitree]], the [[Capital/Legends|capital]]<ref name="jedirefuse" /> of the [[Outer Rim Territories/Legends|Outer Rim]]<ref name="tea">''[[The Essential Atlas]]''</ref> [[Planet/Legends|world]] of [[Ord Thoden]]. When combing the ruins, a team of [[Jedi/Legends|Jedi]] rescue workers found a [[Aris-Del Wari|infant girl]] alive in the wreckage of Domitree, and sensed within the child [[The Force/Legends|Force]] [[Force-sensitive/Legends|potential]]. With no one around to identify her and her parents missing and presumed [[Death/Legends|dead]], the [[Jedi Order/Legends|Jedi]] took her into custody, named her Aris-Del Wari and began the early stages of training her as a Jedi. However, although the Jedi did not know it at the time, the child's mother&mdash;[[Jonava Billane]]&mdash;was in fact alive, and was discovered one [[Standard month/Legends|month]] later convalescing in a town on the outskirts of Domitree. Billane learned that her daughter, originally named Ludi Billane, had been taken by the Jedi, and determined to regain custody of the girl, spent what meager funds she had to travel from Ord Thoden to [[Coruscant/Legends|Coruscant]] and begin a campaign to get her daughter back.<ref name="jedirefuse" />

==The case==
{{Quote|We have opened the child's mind to the larger world of the Force. The child is awakened, and to return it to the birth-parents at this stage would be far too dangerous. It is in everyone's best interests and safety for the child to remain in Jedi custody.|Coleman Trebor|<ref name="jedirefuse" />}}
[[File:LudisMom.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Jonava Billane holding a holo of her daughter Ludi.]]
With absolutely zero precedent for a custody case of this nature, the dispute between Billane and the Jedi Order&mdash;which earned a large amount of media coverage and was popularly termed the "Baby Ludi" case&mdash;proved particularly vexing to the [[Galactic Republic/Legends|Republic]] [[Judicial Department/Legends|Judiciary]]. Backed by the independent grassroots Jedi-accountability watch-group known as the [[People's Inquest]], Billane and her pleas received a popular following, and eventually [[Senator/Legends|Senator]] [[Boganni Hrul]], who represented Ord Thoden in the [[Galactic Senate/Legends|Galactic Senate]], delivered a formal petition to the [[Jedi High Council/Legends|Jedi Council]] for the return of "Baby Ludi" to her mother. Three weeks later, the Council took an uncharacteristic step of addressing the matter publicly. Through a representative, [[Jedi Master/Legends|Jedi Master]] [[Coleman Trebor/Legends|Coleman Trebor]], the Jedi Council refused to return Ludi to her mother, saying that the child had already had her mind opened to the Force and that returning her to Jonava Billane would be dangerous for all involved. The statement met with immediate response from Billane, who held a press conference on the steps of the [[Jedi Temple/Legends|Jedi Temple]] and vowed to continue her fight.<ref name="jedirefuse" />

Over the coming months, the matter continued to receive large amounts of popular attention. Billane's cause was supported by a [[Mothers United March]] on the planet [[Alsakan/Legends|Alsakan]] and a mediathon in the [[Minos Cluster/Legends|Minos Cluster]] that featured a number of celebrity appearances.<ref name="motherslove" /> On top of that, the [[Holodrama/Legends|holofilm]] studio [[Kailio Entertainments]] procured a deal estimated to be worth over 125 million [[Galactic Credit Standard/Legends|credits]] to Billane in order to make a [[Untitled Baby Ludi Project|full-length picture]] on the "Baby Ludi" story, with [[H'drachi]] blockbuster director [[Ch'been]] attached to the project and Kailio contract star [[Harissa Shoti]] rumored to portray Billane.<ref name="ludifeature">{{HoloNetNewsWeb|49|life/13328_3.html|Baby Ludi Feature Slated for this Fall}}</ref> Two months after the Council refused her petition,<ref name="motherslove" /> Billane was invited to appear on the popular [[Eriadu/Legends|Eriadu]] talk show ''[[Essence]]'', for an hour-long feature that bumped a scheduled appearance by<ref name="essenceappear">{{HoloNetNewsWeb|48|jediwatch/13321_2.html|Baby Ludi's Mother to Appear on ''Essence''}}</ref> Senate [[Vice Chair]]<ref name="ep2">{{Film|II}}</ref> [[Mas Amedda]]. Over 25 billion viewers watched the episode, where Billane broke down into tears four times while breathlessly pleading for her daughter's return. The program also featured an appearance by People's Inquest leader [[Thrynka Padaunete]], who had taken on a role as Billane's appearance manager&mdash;the People's Inquest,<ref name="motherslove" /> who had members camped outside the Jedi Temple for months,<ref name="kamparas">{{HoloNetNewsWeb|52|jediwatch/13418_1.html|Baby Ludi Moved to Kamparas}}</ref> took a portion of the proceeds from sales of the program.<ref name="motherslove" />

The uproar around the case eventually led to vivid protest activity by local students. After the Jedi Council refused to return "Baby Ludi," student activists at the [[University of Coruscant/Legends|University of Coruscant]] overloaded the school's [[Datanet/Legends|datanet]] hubs with trillions of pictures of the child, filling the hubs completely and overwriting any files stored by students.<ref name="holoflood">{{HoloNetNewsWeb|47|jediwatch/13314_2.html|Baby Ludi Holos Flood UoC Datanet}}</ref> Shortly after Billane's appearance on ''Essence'', a group of 20 university students wielding [[graffiti-bomb]]s attempted to break into the Jedi Temple, defacing the lobby and pushing into the Second Atrium against two Padawans, until Jedi Masters [[Ki-Adi-Mundi/Legends|Ki-Adi-Mundi]] and [[Plo Koon/Legends|Plo Koon]] managed to pacify them with a Jedi [[Mind trick/Legends|mind trick]]. Afterwards, the unruly group was arrested and taken away by [[Judicial Forces/Legends|Judicial officials]].<ref name="defacelobby">{{HoloNetNewsWeb|51|jediwatch/13411_1.html|Activists Deface Jedi Temple Lobby}}</ref>

==Aftermath==
{{Quote|What have you to hide? Are the vaunted Masters so afraid of us that they must flee with a child they know they have no claim to?|Firris Palbert|<ref name="kamparas" />}}
Throughout the process, the Jedi Council steadfastly refused to budge on the matter, and late one night in [[22 BBY/Legends|22 BBY]] the Jedi Order moved the then-14-month-old "Baby Ludi", along with a class of 19 other students, to a [[Kamparas Jedi Training Center|training center]] on [[Kamparas]]. Although Billane and Padaunete were busy reviewing casting auditions for the Baby Ludi holofeature on [[Kassido]], acting People's Inquest leader [[Firris Palbert]] took the opportunity to further stir [[Anti-Jedi sentiment/Legends|anti-Jedi sentiment]] and suggest that members should continue the protest on Kamparas. Although the Jedi Council once again refused comment, the Republic Judiciary stated that the transfer was a standard part of [[Jedi training/Legends|Jedi training]] and rejected the idea that it was related to any external pressure.<ref name="kamparas" />

==Participants==
===Jonava Billane===
{{Quote|I want to thank everyone who's supported me. Your messages and holos and credit advances have meant so much.|Jonava Billane|<ref name="motherslove" />}}
A native of the Outer Rim world of Ord Thoden, Jonava Billane was thrust from obscurity into the [[The galaxy/Legends|galactic]] spotlight after surviving a destructive groundquake in her home city of Domitree. After spending a month convalescing in an outskirt town, Billane resurfaced and spent what meager funds she had at her disposal to travel to Coruscant and begin a campaign to get her daughter back from the custody of the Jedi Order. Billane's tale inspired a wide amount of sympathy and intense media coverage, and her formal petition to the Jedi Council was personally delivered by Ord Thoden's Senator, Boganni Hrul.<ref name="jedirefuse" /> Her explosive, widely watched appearance on the Eriadu talk show ''Essence'' attracted even more [[Eye/Legends|eyeballs]] to her plight, and inspired further protests.<ref name="motherslove" /> In the later stages of the custody case, Billane was more concerned by handling the upcoming holofilm on the "Baby Ludi" case than the case itself, and was busy reviewing casting auditions when her daughter was removed from Coruscant to Kamparas.<ref name="kamparas" />

===Thrynka Padaunete===
{{Quote|I salute those that continue our efforts. Remember, vigilance. Who watches the watchmen, I ask? I have to go. I have another call.|Thrynka Padaunete|<ref name="defacelobby" />}}
The founder and leader of the populist Jedi-accountability watch-group known as the People's Inquest, Thrynka Padaunete immediately co-opted the "Baby Ludi" case as one of the champion causes of her movement.<ref name="jedirefuse" /> Vocal in her belief that the Jedi Order was a corrupt cult,<ref name="motherslove" /> Padaunete quickly became attached to Billane and prompted a number of Inquest members to set up a months-long protest outside the Jedi Temple.<ref name="kamparas" /> As the case attracted more and more publicity, Padaunete moved away from her role with the People's Inquest, eventually becoming Billane's agent and spokeswoman.<ref name="defacelobby" /> Padaunete eventually became intimately involved in the production of the Baby Ludi holofeature, and was replaced as acting leader of the Inquest by Firris Palbert.<ref name="kamparas" />

===Ludi Billane/Aris-Del Wari===
{{Quote|I believe that a child should be with her mother, and won't stop until I have Ludi back in my arms.|Jonava Billane|<ref name="jedirefuse" />}}
Discovered in the ruins of the city of Domitree on Ord Thoden, Ludi Billane was found by Jedi rescue workers completely alone and with her parents missing and presumed dead. The Jedi quickly noticed her Force potential&mdash;while standard procedure required parental consent before taking a child for training, Billane's status as an apparent orphan prompted the Jedi to take her to Coruscant, name her Aris-Del Wari and begin her initiation into the Jedi Order.<ref name="jedirefuse" /> While her custody case became a hot-button topic, "Baby Ludi" remained at the Jedi Temple, eventually being grouped into a clan of 20 young apprentices that were taken to continue their training on Kamparas.<ref name="kamparas" />

==Behind the scenes==
The "Baby Ludi" custody case appeared in several [[HoloNet News (original website)|HoloNet News]] postings, created to promote the release of the [[2002]] film [[Star Wars: Episode II Attack of the Clones|''Star Wars'': Episode II ''Attack of the Clones'']], the second installment of the ''[[Star Wars]]'' [[prequel trilogy]].<ref name="jedirefuse" /><ref name="motherslove" /> In his original pitch for the HoloNet News website, author [[Pablo Hidalgo]] called the "Baby Ludi" story a trivial one that the media would latch on to in the face of the impending [[Separatist Crisis/Legends|Separatist Crisis]]. He compared the fixation on the story to the real-life examples of [[Wikipedia:Elián González affair|Elián González]], [[Wikipedia:O. J. Simpson murder case|O. J. Simpson]], and [[Wikipedia:JonBenét Ramsey|JonBenét Ramsey]].<ref name="blog">{{Blog|pablog|141|Dusting Off the Archives: Original HoloNet News Pitch}}</ref>

